<DOC><DOCNO> AP880819-0196 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-08-19-88 2133EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-India-Punjab     08-19 0291</FIRST><SECOND>AM-India-Punjab,0301</SECOND><HEAD>Sikh Policeman Kills Two Senior Officers</HEAD><DATELINE>AMRITSAR, India (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A Sikh policeman on Friday shot andkilled two senior officers who suspected he was involved in theSikh insurgency in Punjab state, and was shot dead himself minuteslater, authorities said.   The policeman, Assistant Sub-Inspector Dalbir Singh, was killedby another officer right after he fired, Deputy Inspector-GeneralB.S. Bhullar said.   The shootout occurred at a police station in the town ofPatiala, 160 miles southwest of Amritsar.   Elsewhere in Punjab, eight people were killed Thursday night inattacks blamed on Sikh militants, news reports said.   Bhullar said Sital Das, a senior superintendent of police, andBaldev Singh Brar, a superintendent, were questioning Dalbir Singhabout his suspected ties with Sikh militants when he killed themwith his service revolver.   Inspector Gurdip Singh, who was outside the room, opened thedoor and shot Dalbir Singh, Bhullar said.   Das and Brar were the two most senior police officers in Patialadistrict.   Radical Sikhs have been fighting for an independent homeland innorthern Punjab state since 1982. The community comprises only 2percent of India's 800 million people but is in a majority inPunjab, the country's wealthiest state.   The insurgents claim that Sikhs are discriminated against by theHindus, who make up 80 percent of India's population.   Many policemen in Punjab are Sikhs and some are known to besympathetic to the militants.   The United News of India news agency said the Thursday nightvictims included three Sikhs, one Hindu and four unidentifiedpeople.   The deaths raise to 1,729 the number of people reported killedby Sikh militants in Punjab this year. Moderate Sikhs, accused bymilitants of being traitors, make up more than half of the victims.</TEXT></DOC>